explanation:
OS_CHECK_POINTER (macro) - must inspect the macro expansion to see if it uses compiler-specific extensions (statement-expressions, typeof, __attribute__, inline asm, builtins, or other non-standard constructs).

OS_CHECK_APINAME (macro) - same reason as above; it may expand to checks or logging that use language extensions.

OS_printf (function/macro) - macros above or instrumentation may call OS_printf; its declaration/definition can include compiler-specific attributes (e.g. __attribute__((format(...)))) or it may itself be a macro using extensions.

UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr (test-harness symbols) - the static call graph shows these are invoked (likely by the parameter-check macros or instrumentation). Their implementations or macros may use compiler extensions; include them to inspect any non-standard constructs injected by the test/stub framework.

OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl (function) - need the prototype/definition to verify it does not use non-standard return-type attributes, calling conventions or other extensions.

OS_TaskGetId_Impl (function) - same as above; called to obtain the current task id and its declaration/definition might include extensions.

OS_ObjectIdFindByName (function) - the call at the end is part of the function behavior; its signature or internal implementation (and any macros it uses) could contain language extensions.

osal_id_t, osal_objtype_t, int32 (typedefs) - these type definitions must be inspected for use of compiler-specific typedef extensions (e.g. anonymous structs/unions, typeof-based typedefs, or attributes applied to types).

OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TIMEBASE, OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_STATE (macros/enums) - constants or macros could be defined via non-standard constructs (e.g. complex macros using statement-expressions) or have attributes associated; inspect their definitions.

Rationale: The MISRA rule targets any use of language/compiler extensions anywhere in the code that the target function uses (including macros, called functions, and type definitions). To determine compliance you must inspect the definitions/expansions of every macro, typedef, constant, and called symbol that the function directly or indirectly depends on (including test-stub instrumentation), because extensions might be introduced there rather than in the visible function body.
